<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910212-0057</DOCNO><DOCID>910212-0057.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Reynolds andamp; Reynolds Co.:   Computer Software System   Is Expanded by Company</HL><DATE>02/12/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   REY</CO><IN>SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><LP>   Reynolds andamp; Reynolds Co., looking for a piece of theconsolidated auto dealer market, has expanded its computersoftware system so it can serve 1,000 workstations instead ofjust a few hundred.   The move will allow Reynolds to take advantage of theindustry's trend toward consolidation, company officialssaid. The new computer system will sell for about $2 millionto $3 million, compared with $350,000 to $1 million for thesmaller system.</LP><TEXT>   Reynolds, which is based in Dayton, Ohio, also said itsigned a letter of intent with Mitchell International of SanDiego to link their computer systems so auto dealers can haveaccess to Mitchell's computerized estimate service. The newsystem would be marketed by Reynolds.   Mitchell International is a division of Thompson Corp., aToronto company.</TEXT></DOC>